    <note>Zhu(1) Bian [16681] He was an imperial university student at the time of the Jin invasions and became an officer in the Song army. His first wife, born Chao(2), was killed by [Jin] soldiers. According to Zhu(1) Xi [3257], Chao(2) Yuezhi [3029] liked Bian's poetry and made him a son-in-law of Yuezhi's elder brother. Identified as Xi's granduncle by Xi's sacrificial prayer (Zhu Xi, WJ, 87.19b-20a) and as Song's [11904] uncle in Huizhou FZ, 9.3b-4b. His son-in-law, Wang(2) Zi and Zi's son, Bing (both Wuyuan county residents and not in dataset) are probably members of the same lineage as the Langya Wuyuan Wang(2) [lineages # 1041-2] (q.v.). See Zhu Wenmao, Zhige Zhu Gong cimu lu for detailed biographical data as well as extsant writings. Zhu Xi, WJ, 98.11a-15b. CBD, 565-6.</note>
